I’m such a New Years resolutions gorl - I always have been and likely always will be. This year, after a slow burn of self-realization, self-discovery and an exhausting amount of healing… I’ve decided that I’m getting back to me. I’m getting back into my own skin, back into the core of who I am, unapologetically. I’m getting weird this year. I am done apologizing for who I am or who I was. I am done stressing over what I’m doing right and what I’m doing wrong - what I’ve done right, what I’ve done wrong. I want to learn to say no, and not feel bad for how I feel. I’ve never been much of a rule follower, I don’t know when I became so uptight. What I do know is, I’m so sick of rules and the long lists of who I’m suppose to be, what I’m suppose to look like and what I’m suppose to do. I wanna bust out of my skin at this point. I’m so in and out of my head. I’m long past due realizing something’s gotta change, and deep into the realization that life is so short. Everything could change in the blink of an eye. It’s time I start spending more energy loving and enjoying what I’ve got and who I am.

I’ve spent too much time worrying. Too much time trying to fit into a mold I don’t belong in. I am ready to be me again. I’m ready to let go of perfectionism and transform into the weird fucking fairy I came to this universe to be. I am becoming a sloth, a fairy witchy beautiful colorful sloth if you will. I want to move slow and just hang around and not really care about what’s beneath me. But also I wanna dance, I wanna sing, I wanna spin around and run through fields and let my inner child roam free. I just want to be the wildest, weirdest, biggest version of myself that is yet to exist.

Anyway….

SPACE has huge impact on how we think/feel. To me, the environment of a place matters tremendously. I think what @mothertattooer has done w her tattoo shop demonstrates that power. Stoked to have been able to work on this, the grand opening of @mothershousedallas!

Now that you’ve all seen the place I’d love to finally share the journey of what it took to get us here.

I took a huge leap of faith when I decided to take this project on. I spent a year looking for the perfect place, and spent six months going back and forth with a space on Greenville Ave. After so many hard moments and let downs, I decided to give up on that building. There was this sweet little building on Oak Lawn that we always kept in mind, but the amount of work it needed scared me. I finally decided that it was time to change the route in my plans and go to plan B. Lucky for me, 2512 Oak Lawn Ave. was still there, almost waiting for me. Which at the time I felt devastated by the loss of what plans I had in mind, it ended up being the best decision I ever made.

We spent 10 months building this place. I couldn’t even tell you the amount of things that went wrong, the amount of hurdles I had to jump through — The amount of times I wanted to give up, the amount of times I regretted doing this at all. After ten months of blood, sweat, tears, pain, heartbreak, loss of finances, loss of my mind and absolute exhaustion we finally got to the finish line. While it has been the hardest two year of my life, it is the best reward I could have ever imagined. I would do it all over again. 

Thank you for the two years of hard life lessons that I will keep with me forever. Thank you to my clients who were patient with me during so many transitions and obstacles. Thank you to everyone who helped get me to this point, because I certainly did not do it alone. Every inch of Mother’s House had so much love poured into it and I hope you all feel every bit of it when you’re here.

I had the most incredible birthday week and weekend of my life. The build up to turning 29 was a bit of an emotional roller coaster for me (thank you Saturn return!) but actually turning 29 was an incredible feeling. I felt so loved, so beautiful, so powerful and full of life in a way that I have never felt before. I have worked so hard throughout my 20’s as a very young mother and business woman. I have suffered so much loss and pain throughout my 20’s that at times life felt insufferable, and it’s difficult not to mourn it. I was worried that maybe I had missed out on some of my best years by spending them in the wrong way. Instead, actually celebrating my birthday in my own energy, surrounded by so many incredible and special people to me… reminded me that only the best is yet to come.

I am so grateful and full of love as this week ends. Thank you to my husband, my daughters, my family and my friends for filling my life with so much joy. I am looking forward to celebrating this last year of my 20’s and cannot imagine what magic is yet to come. ✨
